        <p> &nbsp; </p>
        <p> My concentration was only interrupted by a gecko that hid in a bamboo tube in front of me and my camera. He gave such strange sounds of himself and then reinforced by the bamboo that I thought it was somehow that I was still unknown to my new cell phone. The gecko then looked out of the tube every 30 minutes to further annoy me and my camera. </p>
        <p> Another family was sitting next door. After a while they went snorkeling and I heard with an ear how beautiful it was and that is fish everywhere. I think I have to go diving here soon. I hope that my nose will finally be free again soon. </p>
        <p> When my laptop battery was almost empty, it crunched and cracked it quite loudly above me and I heard something bigger came down from the tree. It really banged loudly several times. I just watched to run towards the water and hoped that it was the right direction. </p>
        <p> Yes, it was lucky. After just a few seconds, it was quiet again as if there was never anything. I stopped in front of the water and looked around. I saw this 15 to 20 kg branch lying right next to the table where I was just sitting. On the other side of the Pavilion, there were other branches and parts of the pavilion roof. </p>
        <p> I took a closer look at the roof and found that a nice hole gaped up at the point where I had just sat and only prevented the thicker bamboo strut from hit me. Phew, that was damn tight. </p>
        <p> Many thanks to my guardian angel. Since the battery was all of my laptop and was no longer thinking of concentration, I slowly made my way back to Dumaguete. </p>
        <p> In the evening I worked for the remaining hours and today I was more to bed. </p>
